WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.360
Hey everybody, my name is Cecil and I'm here with Jay and we're part of the Posit Support

00:00:11.360 --> 00:00:19.959
team and today we're going to walk through running a Connect document on the Linux command

00:00:19.959 --> 00:00:20.959
line.

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:26.160
So there may be instances where you have a published application that may have stopped

00:00:26.160 --> 00:00:32.480
working or you'd like to test it on the Linux command line just to rule out the Posit products

00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:38.119
as a variable and there's a relatively easy way to do that.

00:00:38.119 --> 00:00:45.439
First we have to find the data directory that Connect uses and if you haven't set this it

00:00:45.439 --> 00:00:49.759
defaults to var lib rstudio connect.

00:00:49.759 --> 00:00:55.439
You can change this if you like and if you change the base directory then you can just

00:00:55.439 --> 00:01:00.799
change the appended directory on Linux and you can see all your apps.

00:01:00.799 --> 00:01:07.320
So in this example because it's the default we can navigate to this directory and find

00:01:07.320 --> 00:01:08.800
our application.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:13.839
All of our applications will be within this subdirectory and the way we identify it in

00:01:13.839 --> 00:01:18.519
particular is with the content ID.

00:01:18.519 --> 00:01:29.400
So in this case we'll pull up a terminal, we need to do a quarto preview var lib rstudio

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:33.440
connect and we have a bunch of folders in here.

00:01:33.440 --> 00:01:40.480
So for our particular app we'll need to go into the apps folder and we'll be presented

00:01:40.480 --> 00:01:48.000
with a selection of numbers and the number that we need corresponds to the content ID

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:49.760
which in this case is 40.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:56.279
So 68 is just the iteration if you've published multiple renditions of this app that number

00:01:56.279 --> 00:02:02.320
will change but because we only have one we can leave it 68 for now.

00:02:02.320 --> 00:02:04.360
Now here we have all of our files.

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:10.960
Because this is a quarto document we will need to run quarto preview on the QMD file

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:19.600
So this would be demo.qmd and if we run that command it should process and give us a URL

00:02:19.600 --> 00:02:21.039
that we can browse to.

00:02:21.039 --> 00:02:28.000
So it's given us localhost at a randomized port and if we put that into our web browser

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:29.600
that should bring up the same app.

